Does trap type matter?

January 31 2018

  • Univariate analyses
    • Species richness
    • Beetle abundance
    • Shannon Diversity of beetles

  • Concluding remarks

Univariate analyses

See whether greater variance in bait type or trap type?

Species richness

First I will consider the abundance of beetles. Here this is simply the number of beetles observed in each kind of trap after 24h (1 week in FIT).

First I add in the effect of block to the dataset. In my data there were 11 blocks, and I convert it to a factor. I also relevel the intercept to become Standard 25g Human.

lmdata<- read.csv("/Users/mbrown/Documents/Oxford by Year/PROJECT (and stuff)/Analysis/Analysis excel/Linear Model/Linear Model Analysis Trap Type.csv")
lmdata$Block <- rep(1:8, 11)
head(lmdata)
lmdata$Trap.Type<- relevel(lmdata$Trap.Type, "Standard 25g Human")
lmdata$Block<- as.factor(lmdata$Block)
options(scipen=999)

meansandsd <- function(data, y = group){
  meantable <- rep(NA, dim(data)[2])
  sdtable <- rep(NA, dim(data)[2])
  
  for(i in 1:dim(data)[2]){
    if(anyNA(data[,i]) == TRUE){
      data<-data[complete.cases(data[,i]),]
    } else data[,i]
    meantable[i] <- data.frame(tapply(data[,i], INDEX = data[, y], FUN = mean))
    sdtable[i] <- data.frame(tapply(data[,i], INDEX = data[, y], FUN = function(x) sd(x)/sqrt(length(x))))
  }
  
  tables<-cbind(data.frame(unlist(c(meantable))), data.frame(unlist(c(sdtable))))
  tables$Group <- rep(levels(data[, y]), length(names(data)))
  tables$Trait <- rep(names(data), each = length(levels(data[, y])))
  #tables2 <- tables[-c(1:length(levels(data[, y]))),]
  tables2 <- tables[tables$Trait != y,]
  colnames(tables2)[1] <- "Mean"
  colnames(tables2)[2] <- "SEM"
  tables2
}

# calculate means and standard errors
meansandsd(lmdata, y = "Trap.Type")

Richness is nothing fancy here, it is just raw numbers of species per trap. The model below is the same model in general to the models that follow. I have put in a random effect of site, to take into account the differences between ROKAN and LIBO. I have also added in block to take into account block to block variability. The residuals are modelled by a poisson distribution because the data is count data.

Below we see that in the random effects, there is no effect of site (no variance between site!). There is an effect of the block, but it is very small indeed and not even on the scale of the estimates of the fixed effects. In terms of the fixed effects, only the human baited bowl trap and 24 hour FIT had significantly lower species richness.

The anova shows that adding in trap type to the model is significant in explaining the variation. Not sure if this is useful!

library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
fmtrap1.1<- glmer(Richness ~ 1 + Trap.Type + (1|Site) + (1 | Block), data = lmdata, family = "poisson")

Slightly re-vamped plot, that has been plotted many, many times

library(reshape2)
meltdata<- melt(lmdata, id.vars = c("Site", "Bait.Type", "Trap.Type"))
## Warning: attributes are not identical across measure variables; they will
## be dropped
library(plyr)
meltdata$value <- as.numeric(meltdata$value)
standarderrordata<-ddply(meltdata, c("Trap.Type", "Bait.Type", "variable"), summarise,
                       N= length(variable) ,              
                       mean= mean(value, na.rm=TRUE), 
                       sd= sd(value), 
                       sem =sd(value)/sqrt(length(value)))

Multivariate analysis

Ive decided that the best way to go was PCA, its a pretty unambiguous method without any fixation of the distortion of points seen in DCA. The plot is consistent with everything we have seen before, but it plots it all on one graph which is best I think. It shows a cattle community driven by the species within the red ellipse, and a separate human dung community in the blue ellipse. The contributions of individual species to the axes can also be seen.

Before I had another graph which plotted the taxa by themselves and then they were coloured by bait preference on some chi squared tests. I think that really is unneccesary as it can all be depicted in one graph without the need for such calculations (which with bonferroni corrections were all highly non-significant anyway). Arguably, the NMDS plot I had before was nice too as it had the FIT covering both of the other bait types, showing that it was capturing a large range of taxa. Here, I think it shows that it didnt catch very much at all, and not a community comparable to either bait type.

commatrix<- read.csv("/Users/mbrown/Documents/Oxford by Year/PROJECT (and stuff)/Analysis/Analysis excel/Community Matrix Final/Final data transposed names minus pilularis.csv")
